== Minimum (Qubes 3.X) ==
* A 64-bit Intel or AMD processor - <code>x86_64</code> aka <code>x64</code> aka <code>AMD64</code>. <ref> Qubes system requirements are directly sourced from https://www.qubes-os.org/doc/system-requirements/</ref>
* 4 GB RAM.
* 32 GB disk space.
* Legacy boot mode - required for R3.0 and earlier; UEFI is supported beginning with R3.1

== Minimum (Qubes 4.X) ==
* As per Qubes 3.X minimum requirements above, ''plus'':
** Intel VT-x with [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Second_Level_Address_Translation#Extended_Page_Tables EPT] or AMD-V with [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Second_Level_Address_Translation#Rapid_Virtualization_Indexing RVI].
** [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/X86_virtualization#Intel-VT-d Intel VT-d] or [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/X86_virtualization#I.2FO_MMU_virtualization_.28AMD-Vi_and_Intel_VT-d.29 AMD-Vi] (aka AMD IOMMU) - required for effective isolation of network VMs.

== Recommended ==
* A fast SSD - strongly recommended.
* Intel IGP - strongly preferred.
** Nvidia GPUs may require significant troubleshooting.
** ATI GPUs have not been formally tested, but see the [https://www.qubes-os.org/hcl/ Hardware Compatibility List].
* Intel VT-x or AMD-V - required for running [https://www.qubes-os.org/doc/hvm/ HVM domains], such as Windows-based AppVMs.
* Intel VT-d or AMD-Vi (aka AMD IOMMU) - required for effective isolation of network VMs and [https://www.qubes-os.org/doc/assigning-devices/ PCI passthrough].
* TPM with proper BIOS support - required for [https://www.qubes-os.org/doc/anti-evil-maid/ Anti Evil Maid].
* 16 GB+ RAM minimum. 32 GB+ for power users. <ref>Users report problems in creating DisposableVMs and running multiple VMs in parallel with only 4 GB RAM. 8 GB RAM is nearly exhausted with {{q_project_name}} VMs running in parallel with the <code>sys-net</code>, <code>sys-firewall</code> and <code>sys-usb</code> AppVMs.</ref>
* A non-USB keyboard or multiple USB controllers to enable creation of a [https://www.qubes-os.org/doc/usb/ USB VM]. <ref>To prevent malicious compromise of dom0 via USB mice, keyboards or other USB devices.</ref>
* Interrupt remapping - this helps resist potential (hypothetical) attacks coming from compromised driver domains like <code>sys-net</code> or <code>sys-usb</code>. <ref>https://github.com/QubesOS/qubes-issues/issues/3208</ref>

Before purchasing any hardware specifically for Qubes, always check the [https://www.qubes-os.org/hcl/ hardware compatibility list (HCL)] first for suitable models. Without referring to the HCL, there is no guarantee that a computer supporting the above specifications will successfully install Qubes.

Joanna Rutkowska, [https://www.qubes-os.org/news/2018/10/25/thank-you-joanna/ Qubes founder and former project leader], stated in early-2018: <ref>https://twitter.com/rootkovska/status/959743157041811456</ref>

